  "final_analysis": "In the case of a needle stick injury involving exposure to HIV-positive blood, especially from a patient with a very low CD4 count (20/microL) and a high viral load (>10^7 copies/ml), the risk of HIV transmission is significantly elevated. The standard medical response in such scenarios is to initiate post-exposure prophylaxis (PEP) as soon as possible. The recommended PEP regimen typically includes a combination of antiretroviral medications for a duration of 4 weeks. The most effective and widely accepted regimen includes zidovudine (AZT) combined with lamivudine (3TC). While zidovudine alone is sometimes used, the addition of lamivudine enhances the efficacy of the treatment. Acyclovir is not appropriate for HIV PEP as it is not effective against HIV. Therefore, the best course of action is to administer zidovudine with lamivudine for 4 weeks to the nurse to mitigate the risk of HIV infection. This aligns with current medical guidelines and consensus on PEP for high-risk exposures.",
